entry.title: InkOverflow for Spelling and Grammar markers
entry.content:
Add ink overflow calculations for the new CSS-driven spelling and

grammar markers.



* Plumb additional objects, particularly the cursor, through to

the ink overflow calculations for text fragments. These are necessary

to access and render the markers.

* Refactor some methods in ng_highlight_painter to avoid repeated casts and pointer lookup of the document marker controller.

* Refactor the code for test decoration overflow to cover spelling

and grammar (and in the near future custom highlights).

* Add tests for markers in html.



Markers in SVG are still not invalidated correctly because the VisualOverflow code for SVG does not take into account decorations. Attempts to make it use ink overflow need more work, so were left out of this patch. The only way to get a marker in SVG in the world is to employ a hack to make text content editable. It's not a major use case at all, only historically used because foreign object was not supported in IE.



Selection handling is also left for the future.

entry.title: WebGPU: Don't cache the list of Dawn adapters
entry.content:
The list of adapters is re-iterated every time in RequestAdapter.

This a step toward making WebGPU adapters single-use. Once adapters

are invalidated after the first successful call to requestDevice,

then it will not be valid to reuse the old Dawn adapter. It must

be recreated every time.

Internally in Dawn, Adapter creation is a cheap operation that

makes a new light wrapper around the internal PhysicalDevice.

entry.content:
This makes calls to ExecuteJavaScript and CallJavaScriptFunction get

passed onto RenderFrameHostImpl, which is responsible for sending

them over to the renderer.



This also changes the way that WebFramesManager::Observers are

notified about frame creation, to avoid making them aware of frames

that are still in a speculative state, where JavaScript execution is

not allowed (and will trigger a NOTREACHED).

entry.title: Only set Attribution-Reporting-Support header when cross app web runtime feature is enabled
entry.content:
Currently Attribution Reporting API surface is enabled when either

AttributionReporting or AttributionReportingCrossAppWeb runtime feature is enabled, and the cross app web API specific surface

(Attribution-Reporting-Support request header) is gated behind a

base::Feature. This is not ideal because for clients where

network::features::kAttributionReportingCrossAppWeb is allowed, the

AttributionReporting Origin Trial alone is sufficient to enable cross

and and web functionality.



The Attribution-Reporting-Support request header is set in the network

service which cannot access status of runtime features. This CL plumbs

AttributionReportingCrossAppWeb runtime feature status from renderer to

network service to gate Attribution-Reporting-Support header setting.

This is done by adding this field to the request object(s) passed to

network service.



The plumbing to the browser process will be addressed in a follow up CL.

entry.title: [Autofill] Strong type for frontend IDs
entry.content:
This CL is a step towards eliminating "frontend IDs" (aka "unique IDs"

aka "identifiers" in some parts of the code). Currently, Frontend IDs

are raw integers whose sign determines what they represent:

- negative integers are one of the PopupItemId constants;

- non-negative integers can be converted into a BackendId, which

in turn represents an AutofillProfile or CreditCard.



This CL introduces a struct with constructors that distinguish

between between `PopupItemId` and `int`. A followup CL converts

`PopupItemId` in an `enum class` to introduce type safety.



This CL does not introduce any functional change. In particular, the

conversion functions as_int() and as_popup_item_id() are agnostic to

whether the FrontendId was created as an `int` or as a `PopupItemId`.

For example, the following hold:



FrontendId(PopupItemId::kClearForm).as_int() == -4

FrontendId(-4).as_popup_item_id() == PopupItemId::kClearForm



The next steps to eliminate frontend IDs are

1. removing `FrontendId(int)` and `FrontendId::as_int()` (and using

a `BackenedId` in these places);

2. replacing the then-trivial type `FrontendId` with `PopupItemId`.



autofill_agent.mm. Fixing autofill_agent.mm's test coverage isn't

this CL's scope.

entry.title: Show magnifier when selection dragging in Textfield.
entry.content:
The ChromeOS touch selection magnifier is one of the features being

added as part of a ChromeOS touch text editing redesign. See WIP

design doc: go/cros-touch-text-editing (mainly the Magnifier section).

The idea is that the magnifier will make it easier to see the cursor

and text, especially when the user's finger might be partly covering

the cursor/text.



For views::Textfield, we show the magnifier when selection dragging,

i.e. when adjusting the cursor or selection using gestures on the

Textfield.



We add an IsSelectionDragging function to TouchEditable and use this to

determine whether TouchSelectionControllerImpl should show a magnifier

or not. The magnifier zooms in on the focus bound, i.e. the cursor or

selection endpoint being dragged.



Demo:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1TAeP1EOa0oHeO0h8yfXAl6v4fksok8se/view?usp=sharing

entry.title: [text-wrap-pretty] Use `NGLineInfoList`
entry.content:
This patch adds either `NGLineInfo` or `NGLineInfoList` to

`NGInlineChildLayoutContext`, depending on the line breaker

type of the inline formatting context.



Currently, `NGLineInfoList` is used only when `text-wrap:

pretty`, which is a runtime flag not enabled yet.



`NGLineInfo` is a rather large object, ~4k, and

`NGLineInfoList` has 4 instances. As the inline layout may be

nested when it has inline blocks for instance, adding

`NGLineInfoList` only when necessary is important to avoid

stack overflow.



Before this patch, `NGInlineLayoutAlgorithm` allocated one

`NGLineInfo` on the stack, so the stack amount shouldn't

change unless `text-wrap: pretty` is enabled.



This patch should have no behavior changes.

added as part of a ChromeOS touch text editing redesign. See WIP

design doc: go/cros-touch-text-editing (mainly the Magnifier section).

The idea is that the magnifier will make it easier to see the cursor

and text, especially when the user's finger might be partly covering

the cursor/text.



From TouchSelectionControllerImpl, we show the magnifier whenever there

is an active dragging handle. The magnifier zooms in on the selection

bound corresponding to the handle being dragged.



Demo:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Ksas_O5jbUma1cpwI6D8jssuPNZFD06j/view?usp=sharing

entry.title: Rework the supported stream config from MCVD.
entry.content:
MCVD will reject the decoder creation if:

1. The stream is clear.

2. There's no hw decoders for the given config.

3. The config is supported by the bundled software decoder.



As a result, the decoder selection will fallback to the bundled software

decoder, running in the renderer process.



The patch also adds a feature flag to let MCVD use the software decoder

provided by MediaCodec. Cast will enable the feature to avoid video

freeze.



The patch also removes duplicated decoder info from about://gpu.



Bug: internal b/281478323.

Test: vp8 stream playback on ATV (by Cast) and Chromium on Android.
